ll_request": {"url": "https://api.github.com/repos/pytorch/pytorch/pulls/14034", "html_url": "https://github.com/pytorch/pytorch/pull/14034", "diff_url": "https://github.com/pytorch/pytorch/pull/14034.diff", "patch_url": "https://github.com/pytorch/pytorch/pull/14034.patch"}, "body_html": "<p>From <a href=\"https://discuss.pytorch.org/t/whats-the-default-initialization-methods-for-layers/3157/17\" rel=\"nofollow\">this discussion</a> it appears that the linear layer should be initialised according to (LeCun et al., 1998). However, LeCun et al. promote a variance of <code>1/n</code>, rather than a uniform distribution with bounds <code>1/n</code>! Also biases are generally expected to be initialised with zeros.</p>", "body_text": "From this discussion it appears that the linear layer should be initialised according to (LeCun et al., 1998). However, LeCun et al. promote a variance of 1/n, rather than a uniform distribution with bounds 1/n! Also biases are generally expected to be initialised with zeros.", "body": "From [this discussion](https://discuss.pytorch.org/t/whats-the-default-initialization-methods-for-layers/3157/17) it appears that the linear layer should be initialised according to (LeCun et al., 1998). However, LeCun et al. promote a variance of `1/n`, rather than a uniform distribution with bounds `1/n`! Also biases are generally expected to be initialised with zeros.\r\n\r\n"}